(g) Index storage, loading, updation and access cost: Many of the Big RDF systems using an indexing strategy for RDF data storage store the indexed data in a NoSQL database such as HBase on HDFS. However, as HDFS has a default replication of three so an index table is stored three times 37T. Chawla, G. Singh, E.S. Pilli et al. Computer Science Review 38 (2020) 100309 thus increasing the storage space. Also, loading Big RDF data into HBase is very costly and it consumes many re- sources. Savnik et al. [142] and Pan et al. [44] identified that if the dataset is updated frequently then the system will rebuilt the index continually and hence the computa- tional cost of indexing the dataset may exceed the speedup benefit of accessing operations. Leng et al. [143] discussed that some of the issues in storage and indexing of Big RDF data are joins, storage cost and intermediate results. Curé et al. (a) Selecting a suitable storage model for Big RDF data: All the different storage models for RDF discussed above i.e. Triple-based and Graph-based have some limitations. So, selecting a storage structure that is scalable and at the same time suitable for all query types is a tough task. Chuttur et al. [135] discussed the many schemes for RDF storage and identified that selecting a suitable scheme is dependent on many factors. Patchigolla [136] emphasized upon the necessity of selecting a suitable RDF store based on factors such as performance, scalability etc. and de- pending upon the nature of RDF data that an application requires. Also, different storage models are beneficial for different query types. Some frameworks like PRoST [108] use a mixed storage scheme to get benefits of both mod- els. Big RDF frameworks such as HAQWA [94], Hassan et al. [110], Sempala [104], SPARTI [106] etc. owing to their focus on a specific single storage model perform well for star-pattern query types.

(b) Selecting an appropriate partitioning strategy: There is no single partitioning strategy that suits all types of RDF data and all query types. This challenge has been discussed by Pan et al. [44], Akhter et al. [137], Wang et al. [58]. Abdelaziz et al. [43] suggested that a promising research direction is to match the partitioning strategies to RDF graphs instead of using a single partitioning strategy that suits all RDF data graphs and query types. Many Big RDF frameworks like Sempala [104], HAQWA [94] etc. focus on star-pattern queries and thus, use hash partitioning to par- tition Big RDF data. Both the WORQ [105] and SPARTI [106] frameworks partition RDF data based on query workload. While, WORQ tries to efficiently answer queries with un- bound properties by using Bloom filters along with workload-based partitioning, SPARTI does not optimize such queries and instead uses whole RDF dataset for per- forming such queries.

(c) Partitioning and storage cost: Most of the Big RDF frame- works that use sophisticated partitioning heuristics for Big RDF partitioning like Sparklify [84], S2RDF [34] etc. suffer from the high costs of preprocessing. While some other such as SHARD [32], HAQWA [94] etc. which use simple partitioning heuristics like hash partitioning incur high communication cost during query evaluation. Thus, it can be seen that most of these frameworks pay a high cost of data partitioning without taking into regard the query workload. Some of the authors who identified the issues and overhead associated with partitioning large scale RDF data are Harbi et al. [27,60,120], Abdelaziz et al. [43]. Some Big RDF frameworks like PRoST [108], Hassan et al. [110] combine property table and vertical partitioning. Hence, they store RDF data twice by partitioning it in two different ways to guarantee efficient performance for all query types. Many of the Big RDF frameworks do not compute and take into account the extra partitioning overhead. The focal point of all Big RDF frameworks is to achieve efficient query performance.

(d) High communication and I/O cost in distributed query processing: In Big RDF systems, the large scale RDF datasets are processed by partitioning the data among many nodes or machines. The SPARQL queries are also divided into multiple subqueries and are executed separately. The dis- tributed processing of these subqueries requires cross node or inter-partition coordination and high amount of data transfer. During query evaluation this I/O and network communication cost is a heavy burden on the system. Abdelaziz et al. [43], Lee et al. [42], Chen et al. [113], Harbi et al. [27,60,120], Peng et al. [7], Chawla et al. [138] iden- tified that for improving SPARQL query performance over Big RDF data it is important to minimize the inter-node or network traffic thereby minimizing communication costs. Frameworks such as Xu et al. [80], DREAM [23], JARS [24], Ranichandra et al. [74], S2RDF [34] etc. use some query optimizations and try to minimize the communication cost by minimizing the size of intermediate results. JARS [24] performs well for star and simple chain SPARQL queries as it executes these queries locally without any inter-node communication.

(e) Fault Tolerance: One main problem with these Big RDF frameworks is the failure of compute nodes. These frame- works rely on the fault tolerance of the underlying cloud computing tools such as Hadoop. For the Big RDF frame- works using a master–slave model the issue is failure of a single compute node or it might become disconnected from the network. Goasdoué et al. [91] discussed that some of the triples from Big RDF data in case of node failure in a distributed scenario. Thus, fault tolerance is a big challenge in such scenario. Some of the authors like Naacke et al. [96], Hassan et al. [107], Gu et al. [28] identified that Big RDF data management is expected to meet some properties such as scalability, fault tolerance etc.

(f) Scalable SPARQL query optimization and processing: Most Big RDF systems use the traditional relational database solutions for SPARQL query optimization without taking into consideration the structure and size of Big RDF data. Secondly, some of these systems such as S2RDF [34] collect data statistics during RDF data preprocessing for SPARQL query optimization. In such cases, tables need to be maintained for storing the results of pre-computations thus, consuming extra storage space. Some authors who discussed the issue of scalable SPARQL query optimization and processing are Nguyen et al. [139], Zou et al. [12], Kaoudi et al. [140], Atre et al. [141] and Elzein et al. [46].

(h) Large number of intermediate results: A lot of intermedi- ate results are produced when the queries are divided into subqueries and are evaluated locally on different nodes. Lee et al. [42] discussed the high inter-node communica- tion costs associated with transferring large intermediate results of queries across multiple nodes. Wang et al. [58] discussed the heavy burden these large intermediate re- sults bring on both the network and I/O communications. This I/O and network communication cost is a heavy bur- den on the query evaluation. Husain et al. [45] try to address this issue by using a greedy strategy to pick up a join that produces the smallest size of intermediate results. Ranichandra et al. [74] evaluated same sized LUBM and WatDiv datasets. It is seen that when evaluating SPARQL queries larger intermediate results are produced for the LUBM dataset.

- ## SP2Bench
#SP2Bench #Benchmark #Datasets #Performance #Evaluation #Knowledge #Graphs 
The SPARQL Performance Benchmark (SP2Bench) [127] is a language specific synthetic benchmark dataset aimed at a com- prehensive evaluation of the RDF frameworks. This benchmark dataset has a data generator and a set of queries. The data generator of SP2Bench generates large DBLP like documents as it is based on the DBLP library dataset. These DBLP documents are generated in RDF format and they reflect some of the so- cial world relations found in the DBLP database. The SP2Bench dataset has 17 queries that can be evaluated on these documents. These queries vary in characteristics such as selectivity, type of joins, output size etc. and are designed after getting a thorough knowledge of data characteristics. Berlin SPARQL Benchmark (BSBM) [125] is a synthetic bench- mark dataset that is built around the ecommerce use case. Thus, in this use case some products are offered by the different ven- dors and consumers post reviews of those products. The queries imitate the navigation and search pattern of a consumer looking

- ## S2RDF
#S2RDF #Query #Languages #Knowledge #Graphs 
Schätzle et al. proposed S2RDF [34] for RDF Querying with SPARQL on Spark that overcomes the drawbacks of other Big RDF frameworks which favor certain query shapes. It does so by minimizing the input size of query without taking into re- gard its shape and diameter. The data layout proposed in S2RDF is complementary to the vertical partitioning (VP) approach as this layout also distributes triples into relations comprising of two columns (where one is for subject and second one is for object) corresponding to the RDF properties.

- ## SPARQLGX
#SPARQLGX #Query #Languages #Knowledge #Graphs 
SPARQLGX [81] directly compiles the SPARQL queries into Spark operations. For query optimization, SPARQLGX uses its own statistics. Also, there is an additional feature in SPARQLGX named as SDE for direct evaluation of SPARQL queries over Big RDF data without any extensive preprocessing. This feature is valuable in cases of dynamic data or where only a single query needs to be evaluated. In SDE, only the storage model is modified so instead of the predicate files directly the original triple file is searched for query evaluation and the rest of the translation process remains same. This framework maps the triple patterns in SPARQL queries one by one to Spark RDD.
